PURPOSE: To compare the usefulness of transluminal angioplasty coupled with 
thrombectomy versus surgical revision coupled with thrombectomy in the 
restoration and maintenance of flow in thrombosed dialysis access grafts.
MATERIALS AND METHODS: Twenty-four patients undergoing 28 angioplasty procedures 
were retrospectively compared to 24 patients who underwent 33 surgical revisions 
with a minimum 12-month follow-up period. All patients had thrombosed upper-arm 
expanded polytetrafluoroethylene (ePTFE) grafts.
RESULTS: Initial success rates were 88% for angioplasty and 87% for surgery. 
Mean primary patency for angioplasty and surgery was 4.6 and 3.3 months, 
respectively. Mean secondary patency for angioplasty and surgery was 5.4 and 4.5 
months, respectively. These differences were not statistically significant. A 
significantly shorter hospital stay and lower anesthesia requirement were noted 
in the angioplasty group.
CONCLUSION: Transluminal angioplasty coupled with Fogarty thrombectomy is an 
effective alternative to surgical revision for thrombosed dialysis access 
grafts. Angioplasty extends graft life, thereby preserving proximal venous 
outflow sites for future use.

